Title: Provenance
Author: Ann Leckie
My Review:
I love anything Ann Leckie and this was no different but this is the weakest book of her I have read so far.
TLDR:
The plot is action packed, the world rich but I feel the characters are lacking. They lack any real depth or even arc and some of them read different than they should.

The good:
The worldbuilding is superb, Hwae feels like a real place, with geography, history, customs, language...I felt like I really was there in the world.

There is also a mayor point regarding belonging, (provenance) and the choice to live our lives. A point is made that we get to choose how important things are to us whether they have inherent value or not, even if they are fake, what they represent can still be valuable and worth protecting. The same happens with personal history, while we all have a past, we get to choose our own way and make pur own family if we so choose. Which leads me into the bad.


The bad:
The main character is Ingred a human from Hwae, regular human, NOT Radchaii, in fact the difference is brought up several times but she still reads like a Radchaii character, with the same way of seeing the world and reacting to it, except she is obsessed with serbat and not tea, but thats the only difference.

I felt like the rest of the characters had an interesting premise but they were never explored or developed, including Ingred and it feels so wrong. The relationships between the characters also lack development and cohesiveness and the jump from enemies to friends, or from friends to frenemies to associates, with barely any explanation as to how or why. This is particularly glaring as the plot feels like its angling towards the “found family” trope (a favourite of mine) but doesn’t deliver because the relationships are weak and don’t feel impactful.

The character structure also skips some time between chapters which feels like a way to glare over some plot (holes?) and simply avoid giving an explanation.

Title: Facing Codependence: What It Is, Where It Comes from, How It Sabotages Our Lives
Author: Pia Mellody
Additional Authors: Andrea Wells Miller, J. Keith Miller
My Review:
A confirmation bias compendium.
It has no real information, no statistics and no science. Reads like the diary of a flip floppy person who is trying to convince themselves and us that they are “doing the right thing” but never manages as they contradict themselves repeatedly on several instances.

The author stresses the importance of avoiding neglect and providing physical nurturing to children, so making the witholding of food a mayor problem only to say in the next chapter that it’s ok to let the child go hungry if they forget their lunch because it’s discipline.

The same goes for spanking. Huge importance is given to the fact that some ways of hitting are worse for the shame they create than for the actual pain occasioned but the author then goes on to say that light spanking (up to a certain age) and slapping children on the head are an ok way to discipline them.

Mostly nonsensical “spiritual but not religious” new age bs.

I give it 2 stars because at least it has taught me the value of consistency and the consequences of the lack thereof

Title: The Raven Tower
Author: Ann Leckie
My Review:
Another amazing book from Ann Leckie.

Another wise narrator that looks on to events, pretty similar to the Imperial Rach trilogy, but on a high fantasy setting.

The narrative follows two arcs, a human and a divine one, and they intermingle in the most exquisite of thrillers. High on intrigue and mystery, you never really know what is going to happen or what the narrator intends, right up to the end.

Couldn’t put it down, the tempo is great and it never really looses pace but there is a definite acceleration towards the end aiming to the finale.

It has fairly closed ending. Ann Leckie could still write about this universe but the ending was very satifying.

Title: The Ten Thousand Doors of January
Author: Alix E. Harrow
My Review:
A more grown up version of Narnia. The adventures of a girl that finds a door to another world, and all the ensuing hijinks.

I like January, she is a fairly believable protagonist, which means she is not always heroic, or right, she just improvises her way through life.
Her adventures are entertaining enough but I can’t help but feel as If I have read a book and its sequel all in one. Some might find the cyclic narrative amusing but I though it was uninspired. Can’t be mad about it anyway, page 33 warns us that “every story is a love story, if you catch it at the right moment” so its not surprising that we get not just one, but two love stories.

I guess this is what irks me a lot about this book, both love stories are about two random people who fall in love after not having spoken 5 sentences and the book just assumes this is enough motivation in which to hinge the plot and move the story forward. It isn’t.

On that same note, several characters repeatedly dismiss the love and bonds formed over 22 years of living together as a simple “get over it Jane” and this loss is only ever adressed at the very end of the book as a closing afterthought that feels utterly unsatisfying.

I guess self-improvement is not a straight road.

The book does a good job of depicting prejudice and racism and the barriers that those bring, as well as full on adressing white privilege, its add a level of grounding to a novel sometimes all to preoccupied with fantasy to be relatable any other way.

Look, its a quick simple read, not the greates book ever, far from the worst. Very basic plane jane fantasy book.

Title: The Body in Pain: The Making and Unmaking of the World
Author: Elaine Scarry
My Review:
This book can be understood in two halves, the first one is the one that really focuses on the "pain" part of the book, the second part focuses more on how the body acts and is acted upon and self actualized by humans and their societies.

I loved the first part, I struggled through the second, mostly because it starts to delve deep into Hebrew scriptures and Marxism, and while it does and ok job of explaining the context, I felt a bit lost at times, like I was missing knowledge in these areas to fully understand the authors argument (in my case, I'm pretty indifferent to religion so that part got me like wut??)

It's certainly an interesting book that brings about a different point of view of pain and how we use it, both in war and torture and how we talk about it, it simply fails to keep the momentum built into the first part.

It's also a bit overwritten, both because of the highly academic language and because there are points that could have been made and explained in 20 pages that the author insists on dragging over 70, and makes it feel repetitive at times.

Overall, I don't regret reading this book, but it took a good chunk of willpower to get through the second part.

Title: Space Struck
Author: Paige Lewis
My Review:
I don't read a lot of poetry, but I feel like this compilation is fine for anyone getting into it.
Some of the verses hit me hard, right in the feels you might say, "A miracle is anything that god forgot to forbid" or "every experience seems both urgent and unnatural".

I had some difficulties with some of the religious references in the poems, not being well versed in religion myself, but the references are subtle and you don't need to get all of them to understand what is being conveyed, besided, the poems are beautiful anyway, and they feel fresh and new and relevant and dare I say, "woke".

Some deal with some heavy issues but modern and pressing even today.

I recommend this, if you want to try your luck with poetry, maybe you will like it, maybe you won't, but it's short and sweet and you loose nothing in trying.

My Review:
This book is what it says on the tin.
It will not teach you HOW to do anything in 3D, it is not a development book but it offers a great overview of techniques, siftware and industry workflows that are good to know and allow you to see the gaps in your own education as well as how to fix it.

Who this book is for: people interested in how animated movies or 3d things are made, beginners, career changers.

What this book isnt: this is not for experts, people working on the field or people looking to develop their skills in a specific software or learn HOW to do any thing mentioned in the book.

Great starter book, recommend it for beginners.

My Review:
Couldn’t put it down. A tale with heries and villains that are not so rudimentary as to be unsatisfying, magic, real people and a lot of adventures.

You should read it yourself, I don’t want to spoil too much.

The only nitpick is the magic system playing fast and loose with the rules, well there are no rules. There is a hint, barely there of a would have been hard magic rules with Sarkan but it all goes out the window with “and then I improvised a spell with magic I pulled from god knows where because I was already exhausted before”

Even then, the plot and characters are good enough that this becomes a minor inconvenience for hard rules lovers like myself

Title: The Secret Life of Walter Mitty
Author: James Thurber
My Review:
This is probably the shortest thing I have ever read, but it says so much in so little space and time.
Now, you may read this story and think Walter Mitty is just an overgrown kid with a penchant for daydreaming, but he is not, his daydreamed life is so complex and riveting and exciting it coexists in his mind with the real one.
I read this book mainly because it is one of the few out there about maladaptative daydreaming, which has not been yet considered a disorder but trust me that it is. It usually rides hand in hand with depression or anxiety or other mental disorders. I had no idea I suffered from this because I have lived like Walter Mitty for most of my life, I just though it was the normal thing, but it is a problem, what I liked about the book is that it writtes about his daydreams in a way that is enticing and not shaming as well as entertaining and almost heart warming.
It is also super short, so if you dont like it in the end its not like you just lost hours of your life.
I actually wish it had been longer

My Review: This book was written keeping a female teenager in mind. If you are on that demographic you will resonate with it, I know I did. But make no mistake, this book is not one of senseless staring and oh that one stupid first love. This book is written with a perfectly sarcastic sense of humor, which I love, but at the same time keeps a really well defined characters interesting. Zoe is not simply a deify to the Obin, she is also a maybe-not-so-clueless teenager. I did not think a grown man could conjure up such a good and true perspective pf what it is to be a teenager. I was wrong. The book answers a couple of questions left unanswered in the last colony. This is not jus a borig retelling of the story. I think I actually enjoyed this more than the last colony. Definitely give it a try.

Title: The Host
Author: Stephenie Meyer
My Review:
I read this book AFTER watching the movie in search for some redeeming quality. I didnt find one. Not only this book is a copy cat of stephanies other books, meaning its all about a love triangle in which the characters have torturing sentimental relationships.
The good side of things is that is considered scifi(theres a lot of fiction, of you count the aliens, but litle to none science, but hey) and that makes it more appealing to me.
The book has some troubles with the pace with overdrawn scenes from time to time but it overall does a good job, i did find quite amusing the conversations between Wanda and Mel, Mel always having that sarcastical side that i love. I Dont quite get the motivations of the humans to keep fighting when its quite clear that the world is wayyyy better without us and the aliens are perfect in every sense of the world. Overall, my opinion of the movie lowered after reading the book, because it seems that all the blondes were portrayed with jet black hair in the film and the other way around, good thing stephanie was present at casting and filming, just in case the director thought of adapting it right.
You can totally pass on this one.

Title: The Hunger Games (The Hunger Games, #1)
Author: Suzanne Collins
My Review:
4 years ago, when i was going to catch a plane to athens that lovely lady voice informs me over the speakers that my flight had been delayed, again, so instead of having a bitch fit i just headed over to one of those litle aiport libraries, and there it was, trashed in a corner like saying "dont notice me" but it was too late.

i got sooooooo hooked that by the time my flight came out i had already finished it and was looking for the second part before getting into the plane. (not to say that i had a 3-4h delay)

its one of those books that you can see where its going from page one but you still love it anyhow, just because you like where its going, the world building its quite awesome and the pacing great. even if i really liked this book, it cannot compare to the 2 following books, which i liked more, specially the last one.

you should read, even if just to shove off that obnoxious feeling that at least i got after watching the film.

WHY THE HELL ARE U STILL HERE??!!!,GO FETCH IT,THIS BOOK IS A MUST:

Title: The Name of the Wind (The Kingkiller Chronicle, #1)
Author: Patrick Rothfuss
My Review:
this book had me on edge from start to end, you should really give it a try.
the world building is awesome and the characters are pretty well rounded up as well(gotta love Elodin and Auri, when they come in, AUri in later books tho)

Kvothe was born in the edena ruth family(traveling actors and performers) but his whole life changed when he came across an "arcanist" that started teaching him "sympathy", it was all peachy and happy untill the Chandrian come in and flat out kill everyone except for Kvothe, that is on the run, alone...this is where it beggins, the race to earn a living and hone his skills...
should defenetly read it!

Title: My Life as a White Trash Zombie (White Trash Zombie, #1)
Author: Diana Rowland
My Review:
finally something out of the classic zombie infection apocalipse topic.
the book really does give some interesting new insights on zombies, taking on real life zombie perspective. but note, its not recommended for sensitive people, as some feeding scenes are gross and you may be overwhelmed, if ur made of iron just like me, then go for it^^
